to prepare the histogram for the two groups and calculate the mean and standard deviation, we can use python programming language and its data analysis libraries such as numpy and matplotlib. here's the python code to accomplish this:  ```python import numpy as np import matplotlib.pyplot as plt  # group a data group_a = [82, 76, 89, 84, 69, 77, 84, 95, 89, 84]  # group b data group_b = [77, 88, 70, 85, 90, 83, 83, 76, 94, 83]  # calculate mean and standard deviation for group a mean_a = np.mean(group_a) std_a = np.std(group_a)  # calculate mean and standard deviation for group b mean_b = np.mean(group_b) std_b = np.std(group_b)  # plotting the histograms plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))  # histogram for group a plt.hist(group_a, bins=10, alpha=0.5, label='group a') plt.axvline(mean_a, color='r', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='mean a') plt.xlabel('scores') plt.ylabel('frequency') plt.title('histogram - group a') plt.legend()  plt.show()  # histogram for group b plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6)) plt.hist(group_b, bins=10, alpha=0.5, label='group b') plt.axvline(mean_b, color='r', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='mean b') plt.xlabel('scores') plt.ylabel('frequency') plt.title('histogram - group b') plt.legend()  plt.show()  # print mean and standard deviation for both groups print('group a - mean:', mean_a) print('group a - standard deviation:', std_a) print('group b - mean:', mean_b) print('group b - standard deviation:', std_b) ```  the code above will generate two histograms, one for group a and one for group b, along with vertical dashed lines indicating the mean score for each group. it will also print the mean and standard deviation for both groups.  you can run this code in a python environment, such as jupyter notebook or google colab, to visualize the histograms and obtain the mean and standard deviation values for each group.
